<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>crassifolius</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Adenostoma</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>glauca</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>leucodermis</i>, <i>Cercocarpus</i> <i>montanus</i>, <i>Diplacus</i> <i>aurantiacus</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Hesperoyucca</i> <i>whipplei</i>, <i>Heteromeles</i> <i>arbutifolia</i>, <i>Keckiella</i> <i>antirrhinoides</i>, <i>Malosma</i> <i>laurina</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>berberidifolia</i>, <i>Rhus</i> <i>ovata</i> and <i>Salvia</i> <i>mellifera</i>. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Quercus</i> <i>agrifolia</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 3.5 m; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Herbaceous layer is open. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li>Both <i>Ceanothus crassifolius</i> and <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum</i> have 30%-60% relative cover in the shrub canopy (cf. Gordon and White 1994, Klein and Evens 2005).</li>
		
		<li><i>Ceanothus crassifolius</i> > 60% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Gordon and White 1994).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Slopes, often south facing. Soils are shallow and rocky.  </div>
</div>

        
