<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ceanothus crassifolius </i>is an evergreen shrub with rigid branches that attains 3.5 m in height. It is an obligate seeder that produces a long-persisting seed bank. As with similar <i>Ceanothus </i>species, at 5 years, shrubs begin producing seeds, which are explosively shed from the plant as the capsule breaks. Most of the seed drops beneath the crowns of the shrub, but some land far from the plant. Seed predation by small mammals and insects may be high (Quinn 1994). Under periods of prolonged drought, outer canopy branchlets may undergo progressive dieback (Davis et al. 2002). <br/>
<br/>
Two intergrading varieties exist, var. <i>crassifolius </i>with lower leaf blades densely tomentose and var. <i>planus </i>with lower leaf blades sparsely tomentose (Fross and Wilken 2006). They have similar ecology, so we include both in this alliance. <br/>
<br/>
Monotypic stands of <i>C. crassifolius </i>occur in post-fire situations where the fire cycle averages 20-25 years. Older stands are invaded by <i>Heteromeles arbutifolia </i>and <i>Quercus berberidifolia, </i>though <i>C. crassifolius </i>shrubs can persist for more than 100 years (Keeley 1992a). Mixed stands of <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum </i>with <i>C. crassifolius </i>tend to occur on south-facing slopes on granitic and metamorphic substrates. They occur in areas with recent fire disturbance, usually within the last 60 years, and in areas with frosty winter nights. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
