<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Ceanothus crassifolius </i>is an obligate seeder, and heat from a fire stimulates seed germination (Quick 1959). Thousands of seedlings establish after fire in the rainy season (Horton and Kraebel 1955, Keeley and Soderstrom 1986). Dense stands of this alliance develop within 10-20 years after a fire. Depending on the site history, <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum </i>may reach cover similar to that of <i>C. crassifolius</i>. Stands begin to self-thin after 20 years, and <i>C. crassifolius </i>can exhibit more than 50% die-off (Riggan et al. 1988). Accumulation of dead branches in older stands increases the possibility of high-intensity fires with time. <i>C. crassifolius </i>will reoccupy sites with moderate- to highintensity fires, while <i>A. fasciculatum </i>is stimulated at lower-intensity fires (Gordon and White 1994).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Medium (10-100 years)
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
