    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-b, Be-g, Bi). Stands exist in the higher elevations of the Santa Monica Mountains, in the Simi Hills (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006), and in the Santa Ynez Mountains (Borchert et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-d, Bf-g, Bj-l, Bn-o). Stands occur in the San Rafael, Santa Ynez, and Topatopa mountains (Borchert et al. 2004), in the Cleghorn Canyon RNA (Cheng 2004), in western Riverside Co. (Klein and Evens 2005), in central San Diego Co. (Evens and San 2005), and generally in the section (Gordon and White 1994).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ceanothus crassifolius </i>can have intense, fast-spreading, and potentially large fires, and fire intensity increases as stands mature. Stands develop fuel loadings capable of supporting moderately intense fires within 15-20 years. High mortality of both seedlings and sprouts is likely when fires recur on burns seeded to annual grasses. <i>Lolium perenne, </i>a grass commonly used for re-vegetation following fire, inhibits seedling establishment and shrub growth. The presence of grass increases the likelihood of early burns. Fires occurring at short intervals have the potential to cause significant changes in species density and composition (Odion and Davis 2000). Although <i>C. crassifolius </i>can persist in the seed bank for many years, shrubs tend to senesce after 60-80 years. A very long interval without disturbance favors <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum. </i> </div>
</div>

    

    

